Narrative:
On August 3, 2023, Toyota received an allegation related to this crash from the vehicle owner. The owner alleged that her son was driving with his girlfriend at the time of the accident. She stated they were on the [XXX] in Northridge, CA in the far left lane. Additionally, she stated that, "He had turned on the cruise control setting and set it at 70 MPH. He had been cruising for about 10 minutes when all of a sudden, the vehicle veered to the left and hit the center divider." The owner stated that all the airbags deployed except for the driver's airbag. The police responded, but the customer did not have details related to the law enforcement entity or whether a report was created. The driver and passenger sustained injuries described as (Driver): bruised knee and left foot injury, (Passenger): Bruising from seatbelt.  ADAS Level 2 driving status was not reported by the owner.
On August 18, 2023, Toyota completed a vehicle inspection with field report for the crash event and obtained the Vehicle Control History (VCH) indicating that ADAS L2 was engaged in the recorded moments prior to the crash. The VCH recording contains approximately 8 seconds of pre-crash data and images. From the VCH, Toyota observed the following: The vehicle was travelling in the center of 3 lanes before drifting left and contacting the concrete highway divider. Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) was engaged from the start of the recording until the crash occurred. Lane Trace Assist (LTA) was engaged  approximately 3.6 seconds prior to the crash event when it disengaged. The field report shows that both Curtain Shield Airbags and the Driver Side Airbag were deployed.

Narrative:
The driver of the vehicle initially contacted the MBUSA Customer Assistance Center ("CAC") on June [XXX], 2023, stating that he was driving his MY2022 GLC300 in Pennsylvania using "driver assistance" and the vehicle drove to the roadside and hit a power pole on the right-hand side of the vehicle. No injuries were reported. The CAC requested additional information from the customer, who responded on July 11, 2023, providing additional information regarding the incident. The customer alleges he was driving to Johnstown, Pennsylvania from North Carolina at approximately 40 to 50 miles per hour using the driver assist function with steering assist (a Level 2 ADAS, triggering the SGO reporting requirement). He further alleges that at approximately 11:30 pm, while driving on a section of roadway in Bedford, PA that curved to the left, "all of a sudden, the car was going off the road to the right hand side, hitting a power pole with the front passenger side". The driver stated he was not injured and that he did not have time to respond to the vehicle's departure from the roadway, CPA ("Collision Prevention Assist") did not engage, and vehicle airbags deployed. The vehicle was determined to be a total loss by the customer's insurance company. The driver stated that he observed no instrument cluster messages prior to, or after the incident. MBUSA is continuing its investigation of the alleged incident.
In accordance with the requirements of the SGO, MBUSA is submitting this 5-day incident report. This report is based entirely on the customer's description and allegations. MBUSA has not confirmed or verified this account or any of its allegations.

Narrative:
The information contained in this report is based solely on Nissan's understanding of the allegations received during customer's discussions with Nissan Consumer Affairs representatives.  Nissan has requested inspection of the subject vehicle and will be investigating further.
On 6/[XXX]/2023, Claimant orally reported that he was driving the subject vehicle with ProPilot Assist (PPA) system on when the vehicle began to veer into the other lanes.  Claimant reportedly attempted to turn the PPA system off but the buttons and brakes stopped working, and the vehicle crashed into a tollbooth.  Claimant reported severe damage to the passenger side and front of the vehicle and airbag deployments. Claimant reported bruising injuries and chest pain but stated he had not seen a doctor yet. 
During a follow-up call on 6/[XXX]/2023, the Claimant stated he was traveling from Sacramento towards San Francisco. Claimant alleges he was stuck in traffic and activated the PPA system at 65 mph, but as he approached the bridge for the tollbooth, he began pressing the button to lower speed.  He alleges the vehicle would not slow down, the steering wheel would not turn, and the brake pedal "became hard", and the vehicle continued to accelerate. Claimant alleges the wheel finally let go, but the vehicle hit one side of the tollbooth.  Claimant reported he was transported to the hospital via ambulance.  
Nissan has requested a vehicle inspection. The inspection date is currently being arranged.
As of June 30th, Nissan is continuing to work with the customer for access to inspect the vehicle. Our offices will re-open on July 5th.
As of July 14th, Nissan is awaiting customer's response to a proposed inspection date next week.

Report Type: 5-Day
Narrative:
Verbatim text of initial customer complaint as recorded by Mazda Customer Experience Center representative is provided:
"Customer states he set the vehicle driver assist to "traffic jam" mode while driving on the highway on his way home from a concert when he tapped the gas and the vehicle darted forward hitting the vehicle in front of him. Customer believes the vehicle malfunctioned and caused the accident on it's own. Customer will have the vehicle brought to ROMANO MAZDA to have the vehicle diagnosed for any issues."
Additional verbatim text of follow-up inquiry by Mazda Customer Experience Center representative to customer is provided:
"The customer stated that he was in the right lane and he wanted to merge into the left lane customer stated as he turned his head for a min to check before merging over the car in front of him stopped really fast and his car just reveled up to 20 mphs for no reason he stated that the car just took off and hit the car in front of him he stated that he didn't hit the gas or anything he stated everything happened so fast that he couldn't even hit his breaks to try to stop the car. The customer stated that everything is still a little fuzzy to what happened. ( The 1st time the customer was telling me what happened he stated that the car that was in front of him was at a complete stop and his car just took off for no reason the customer also stated that when he got on the highway about 10-15 minutes of driving, he had turned the system on and set if for 20 mph but nothing happened he stated then while driving the car did a couple jumps then took off and hit the car in front of him"
Points of clarification/interpretation in order to explain the details of this incident are provided:
"Traffic Jam" Mode was used to describe Mazda's Traffic Jam Assist (TJA) ADAS-2 function, which is alleged to have been operating for some time prior to the crash.
The driver indicated the TJA function was active while driving on the highway, at some point the driver disengaged the TJA function by applying brakes for unknown reasons, followed by reactivating TJA at a later point.
Eventually the reported crash occurred.
No injuries were reported as a result of the incident.
No air bags were deployed as a result of the incident.
The subject vehicle was towed away from the incident scene.

Report Type: 1-Day
1-Day
1-Day
Narrative:
Toyota received an allegation related to this crash on April 11, 2023, and later on April 14, 2023 from the owner and driver of the vehicle through a call to the Toyota Brand Engagement Center. The contact record indicates that the owner alleged he was driving on [XXX] when the vehicle, "veered off the road somehow and crashed into a field." The owner's primary allegation was related to the airbags not deploying. He also mentioned being, "uncomfortable with the steering corrections and with lane departure." The owner described his injuries as a concussion and a partially collapsed lung. Additionally, the owner stated that the White City Police Department responded to the incident and created Police Report # SP23096093. On April 28, 2023, Toyota completed a vehicle inspection and field report for the incident. There were no allegations made related to the Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) or Lane Trace Assist (LTA). However, on May 2, 2023, after additional analysis of the recorded vehicle data, Toyota determined the case was reportable under the SGO. 
Toyota obtained Vehicle Control History (VCH) and Event Data Recorder (EDR) data from the subject vehicle. VCH provides an approximately 7 second pre-crash recording, and EDR provides an approximately 4.7 second pre-crash data recording. Based on the data obtained, the following information was observed: The driver seat belt status was OFF (unbuckled) during the recording. LTA was engaged during the recording from approximately 4 seconds until approximately 1.6 seconds prior to the crash event. At the time of LTA disengagement, the driver turned the vehicle left at a steering angle increasing from approximately 4.5 degrees to 88.5 degrees. DRCC was engaged during the recording until approximately 0.8 seconds prior to the crash event. No FCW or AEB activation occurred. 
As a result of the crash incident, the subject vehicle's curtain shield airbags deployed, the front seatbelt pretensioners deployed and were locked in the retracted position, and it was towed from the crash scene. The front driver and passenger airbags did not deploy.

Narrative: A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was proceeding northbound on [XXX] in stop-and-go traffic through an active construction zone. At the same time, an e-scooter traveling near the right curb was passing other slow traffic behind the Zoox vehicle. Before the e-scooter could also pass the Zoox vehicle on the right, the e-scooter weaved away from the curb, seemingly to avoid a drainage grate, and came within a close following distance behind the Zoox vehicle. As the Zoox vehicle came to a stop again for traffic ahead the e-scooter rider did not stop, and the e-scooter made contact with the right rear tail light of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider remained upright, did not stop to exchange information, and immediately rode off while the Zoox vehicle was still stopped. There were no injuries and police were not called. The damage to the Zoox vehicle was limited to a cracked tail light lens.

Report Type: 1-Day
Narrative:
On February [XXX], 2023, Toyota received an allegation related to this crash from the owner of the vehicle through a call to the Toyota Brand Engagement Center. The contact record indicates that the owner alleged that, "She was driving home from work and was going down on a ramp from a highway. As she was turning on the ramp, she proceeded to turn the steering wheel to turn the vehicle along the ramp. When she was turning the steering wheel, she noticed that the wheels of the vehicle would not turn with it. She kept going straight and ended up hitting a wall and bounced into a ditch." On March 14, 2023, Toyota completed a vehicle inspection and field report on the incident. There were no allegations made related to the Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) or Lane Trace Assist (LTA). However, on March 24, 2023, after additional analysis of the incident details, Toyota determined the case was reportable under the SGO.
Toyota obtained Vehicle Control History (VCH) and Event Data Recorder (EDR) data from the subject vehicle. VCH provides an approximately 7 second pre-crash data recording, and EDR provides an approximately 4.7 second pre-crash data recording. Based on the data obtained, the following information was observed: LTA was engaged during the recording from approximately 6 seconds until approximately 3 seconds prior to the crash event, at which point the driver's steering input disengaged the system. At the time of LTA disengagement, the driver turned the vehicle right at a steering angle increasing from 53 degrees to 465 degrees. DRCC was engaged during the recording until approx. 1.7 seconds prior to the crash event. No FCW or AEB activation occurred.
As a result of the crash incident, no airbags deployed in the subject vehicle and it was towed from the crash scene.

Report Type: Update
Narrative:
*2/25/23: 1-Day Incident Report*
Customer contacted Kia Customer Care on 2/[XXX]/23 & reported that he was driving his 22 Kia Sorento 65mph on [XXX] near Meridian, CT when he fell asleep.  Customer stated he heard beeping, went to hit the brakes but it was too late & his vehicle rear ended the vehicle in front of him. The driver & passenger airbags deployed. The customer reported him & his wife were taken to the ER via ambulance. He reported that his upper body was sore (mostly wrist & left hand) & that his wife sustained a swollen ankle & bruising on the right side of her body. The vehicle was towed. Customer stated that he believed the accident was his fault but claims the Forward Collision Avoidance (FCA) system in this vehicle was not working properly. 
The subject 22 Sorento is equipped with Highway Driving Assist (HDA). HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance & speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway & helps keep the vehicle between lanes while driving. Narrative:
Some entries in this report are based on unconfirmed allegations. On January 18, 2023 Toyota completed a field report related to this crash incident, in which the owner's allegation was related to Pre-Collision System (PCS) non-activation. The owner alleged she was driving on [XXX] westbound through the [XXX] intersection, "when another vehicle entered the intersection to her left, driving at a high rate of speed." She also claimed that she, "had a green light, and the other vehicle ran a red light," and she, "struck the other vehicle in its right side with the front of her Lexus." After the initial impact, the owner's vehicle "spun to the right, then came to a stop." The owner alleged that her, "vehicle's Pre-Collision System should have stopped the car and avoided the accident," and the, "PCS system did not function."
There were no allegations made related to the operation of Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) or Lane Trace Assist (LTA). However, upon obtaining and reviewing VCH and EDR data from the crash event, Toyota became aware that the vehicle was operating with ADAS L2 engagement in the moments leading up to the crash event. VCH provides an approximately 7.9 second pre-crash data recording, and EDR provides an approximately 4.8 second pre-crash data recording. Based on the data obtained, the following information was observed: LTA was engaged from the start of the recording until approximately 1 second prior to the crash event. DRCC was engaged from the start of the recording until the crash event. The PCS warning (FCW) did not activate during the recording of the event. Automatic Emergency Braking (AEB) did not activate during the recording of the event. 
As a result of the crash event, multiple airbags deployed in the owner's vehicle which was towed from the scene. The owner claimed that she, "could not breathe because of the accident. She said her left wrist was bruised, her left knee is sore and her ribcage hurts."

Narrative:
Following receipt of 10/27/2022 VOQ#5 (ODI 11491182), involving a 2022MY EV6, Kia attempted to identify the VIN which was completed on 10/31/22.  The VOQ alleges that the vehicle was being driven on the freeway with lane keep assist and adaptive cruise control when the customer took his eyes off the road to grab something from the backseat and claims the system either disengaged without warning or decided to steer to the left.  Customer further alleged the vehicle drifted 2 lanes to the left and made an impact with the center road barrier resulting in the deployment of the airbag and non-specified injuries.  Customer further alleges that the HDA (Highway Driving Assist) may not have been functioning properly.  Customer did not contact Kia regarding the incident.  The vehicle was instead located by Kia at a Copart facility.  Kia Customer Care is in the process of reaching out to the insurance company to obtain permission to inspect the vehicle.  Kia has no further information at this time.
***11/9/2022 10-Day Update Report***
Kia is tentatively scheduled to inspect the subject vehicle located at the Copart facility in San Martin, CA. on November 17, 2022.  At that time, Kia will also download/read available EDR data.  As a result, Kia has no additional information at this time.  In addition, Kia has not received any contact from the customer.
***12/15/2022 Monthly Update Report***
Kia North America Safety Engineers inspected the subject EV6 vehicle (VOQ 11491182) on 11/17/2022 at Copart, San Jose in San Martin, CA. Based on the inspection and the EDR report, no faults were found with any of the vehicle's systems and appears to be lack of driver control as mentioned by the driver in the VOQ. And per Matthew Yandrick of ODI's request, a copy of the EDR report was provided to NHTSA via the secure link-SLFTS under confidentially on 11/30/2022.
***1/17/2023 Monthly Update Report***
On 1/4/2023, Kia received an email from ODI Electronics Engineer, Matthew Yandrick, requesting additional information regarding this incident.  Below are the 3 questions from Matthew and Kia's responses which were provided to Matthew on 1/11/2023:
1)Was the steering angle parameter recorded? The EDR shows a steering input parameter.
Kia response: Yes, steering angle parameter is recorded and is identified on the report as being 0 degrees which represents a steering wheel pointed approximately straight ahead and is not a null value. Note that the steering angle is reported in increments of 5 degrees in the EDR of this vehicle.
2)The consumer alleges Lane Keep Assist was engaged. Has Kia been able to confirm this?
Kia response: No. There is no data in the EDR of this vehicle regarding any Lane Safety function status, and we have not been able to confirm if it was engaged at the time of the crash. Also, due to front end damage causing system errors, engineers were unable to access the driver-selectable settings for LKA to determine the function status (Off, Warning Only, or Active Assist).
3)The consumer alleges the incident occurred on a multi-lane road with a center barrier. Can Kia confirm the location of the incident? 
Kia response: This was an incident initiated from a VOQ and not by a communication from the consumer to Kia and thus Kia did not receive the location information.  However, in light of your request, Kia has attempted to reach out to the consumer to see if such information is available and awaiting response.

Narrative: On December [XXX], 2022 Toyota received a field report related to this crash incident, in which the owner's allegation was related to airbag non-deployment. During the crash event, the vehicle was rear-ended by an SUV, then crashed into the back of a passenger car. There were no allegations made related to the operation of the ADAS systems. However, upon obtaining and reviewing VCH and EDR data from the crash event, Toyota became aware that the vehicle was operating with ADAS L2 engagement in the moments leading up to the crash event. VCH provides an approximately 9 second pre-crash data recording, and EDR provides an approximately 4.8 second pre-crash data recording. Based on the data obtained, the following information was observed: Lane Trace Assist (LTA) was engaged during the recording until approximately 4 seconds prior to the crash event. Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) was engaged during the recording until approximately 2.4 seconds prior to the crash event, at which point the PCS Alarm (FCW) was activated. The vehicle was traveling at approximately 70 MPH prior to applying the brakes. As a result of the crash incident, the vehicle was towed away from the scene. The owner alleged the vehicle's driver was experiencing, "back pain and headaches."

Narrative:
Following receipt of 10/27/2022 VOQ#5 (ODI 11491182), involving a 2022MY EV6, Kia attempted to identify the VIN which was completed on 10/31/22.  The VOQ alleges that the vehicle was being driven on the freeway with lane keep assist and adaptive cruise control when the customer took his eyes off the road to grab something from the backseat and claims the system either disengaged without warning or decided to steer to the left.  Customer further alleged the vehicle drifted 2 lanes to the left and made an impact with the center road barrier resulting in the deployment of the airbag and non-specified injuries.  Customer further alleges that the HDA (Highway Driving Assist) may not have been functioning properly.  Customer did not contact Kia regarding the incident.  The vehicle was instead located by Kia at a Copart facility.  Kia Customer Care is in the process of reaching out to the insurance company to obtain permission to inspect the vehicle.  Kia has no further information at this time.
***11/9/2022 10-Day Update Report***
Kia is tentatively scheduled to inspect the subject vehicle located at the Copart facility in San Martin, CA. on November 17, 2022.  At that time, Kia will also download/read available EDR data.  As a result, Kia has no additional information at this time.  In addition, Kia has not received any contact from the customer.

Narrative:
On October [XXX], 2022 at 1:35 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle  ("Waymo AV") Peterbilt Class 8 semi-truck and trailer, operating in Tempe, Arizona was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle on [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in autonomous mode on southbound [XXX] and an SUV was traveling ahead of the Waymo AV in the right adjacent lane.  The SUV approached stopped traffic in its lane and struck a passenger vehicle.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode.  The passenger vehicle that was struck by the SUV spun 90 degrees counterclockwise and was pushed partially into the Waymo AV's lane, making contact with the right side of the Waymo AV and trailer.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  The Waymo AV, trailer, and passenger vehicle sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an airbag deployed (in the passenger vehicle) and a vehicle involved was towed away.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of WaymoLLC-20221023-0 (rev.20221024203214).

Narrative:
On August [XXX], 2022, Toyota received an allegation related to this crash from the owner of the vehicle through a call to the Toyota Brand Engagement Center. The contact record indicates that the owner alleged that, "his daughter told him that she was traveling down a hill towards a curb at the bottom of the road when suddenly and unexpectedly the steering assist completely locked up on her preventing her from being able to steer the vehicle." Guest stated that she ended up loosing [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] control of her brand new (2022 Toyota Camry) vehicle causing her to spin out of control and into a ditch." Three other occupants were in the vehicle at the time the incident occurred. On August [XXX], 2022, Toyota completed a vehicle inspection and field report on the incident. On September [XXX], 2022, after additional analysis of the incident details, Toyota determined the case was reportable under the SGO.
Toyota obtained Vehicle Control History (VCH) and Event Data Recorder (EDR) data from the subject vehicle. VCH provides an approximately 7.9 second pre-crash data recording, and EDR provides an approximately 5 second pre-crash data recording. Based on the data obtained, the following information was observed: Lane Trace Assist (LTA) was engaged during the recording until approximately 5.5 seconds prior to the crash event. At the time of LTA disengagement, the driver turned the vehicle left at a steering angle increasing from 9 degrees to 49.5 degrees. Dynamic Radar Cruise Control (DRCC) was engaged during the recording until the crash event occurred. 
As a result of the crash incident, no airbags deployed in the subject vehicle and it was driven from the crash scene. 1 occupant was reportedly taken to the ER for headaches and potential concussion.
This report is a 10 Day update. The original report ID is 1306-3876-1.

Report Type: 1-Day
Narrative:
As reported by Argo AI to Ford on September [XXX], 2022 (Report # 30290-3913-1), an Argo AI Autonomous Vehicle ("Argo AV") was impacted by a cyclist while traveling east on [XXX] and approaching [XXX]. The Argo AV was traveling in its lane adjacent to a cyclist who was traveling in a marked bike lane. As the Argo AV was passing the cyclist (while maintaining more than 2 meters of lateral margin), the cyclist veered left into the Argo AV's lane. In response, the Argo AV steered away from the cyclist, but the cyclist continued into the lane and the bicycle's left handlebar made contact with the Argo AV's passenger side door handle. The Test Specialist brought the AV to a stop. The cyclist maintained balance, continued to cross the lanes behind the stopped Argo AV, and left the scene after a brief conversation with the left seat Test Specialist, during which the cyclist indicated that he was fine and apologized. The Argo AV sustained minor damage to its passenger side door handle.
"Other" data availability: test vehicle data

Report Type: 1-Day
Narrative:
On September [XXX], 2022, a Kia Customer Care Center (CC) agent was dispatched a case where the customer is alleging the "collision assistance feature did not follow through" resulting in a rear end collision with a 2022 Ford Expedition.  Customer alleges he was traveling approximately 50mph on [XXX] with a following distance of 60-80ft with various safety features active including lane keeping assist, Forward Collision Avoidance and adaptive cruise control.  The customer stated the Expedition had a broken taillight and it was difficult to determine whether the vehicle was slowing down.  Customer noticed his Kia EV6 was not slowing down as his vehicle was approaching the Expedition at approximately 40ft causing him to manually pressed on the brakes.  Customer reported that after depressing the brakes, the collision avoidance alarm sounded but the brakes felt "spongy".  Customer alleges the system did not apply what the customer believed to be maximum braking power, even though he had the brakes fully depressed.  Customer rear-ended the Expedition at 15mph. The customer's vehicle was towed.  When asked by CC, the customer reported that HDA and cruise control were engaged at the time of the incident but the customer did not allege that either of those systems caused the accident. 
The subject Kia EV6 is equipped with the ADAS Level 2 Highway Driving Assist (HDA).  HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance and speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway and helps keep the vehicle between the lanes while driving.  However, there is no indication from the facts currently available that the HDA system was not working properly.  Kia is currently working on scheduling an inspection of the vehicle.

Narrative:
Subject Vehicle is a Lucid-owned vehicle used by Lucid employees and contract drivers to test and validate ADAS features under development by Lucid. The Subject Vehicle included Lucid "Highway Assist" (HWA) which is Level 2 ADAS technology under development by Lucid in collaboration with its suppliers. The HWA function combines lane-keeping and Adaptive Cruise Control (ACC), but is not yet available on vehicles that Lucid sells to the public. As a Level 2 technology, HWA requires the attention of the driver at all times and is not expected to avoid all accidents.
 
On 7/[XXX]/2022 at approximately 3:58 am, a contract test driver was driving a Lucid Air northbound on [XXX] at 70 MPH. The driver reported that he engaged HWA and subsequently fell asleep. Telemetered data confirms engagement of HWA and indicates that the driver imparted sufficient torque on the steering wheel to override HWA. When HWA is overridden, it no longer provides lane-keeping and ACC remains active. Approximately 15 seconds later, the vehicle drifted out of its lane and impacted its left side against the roadside barrier on the left side of the road. The driver awoke after the impact and brought the vehicle to a stop on the side of the freeway. Lucid roadside assistance was contacted to tow the vehicle. No airbags deployed. There were no other vehicles or people involved in this accident and the driver was not harmed.

Report Type: 10-Day Update
Narrative:
A HATCI engineer was operating the subject prototype GV70 vehicle evaluating different drive modes (ECO, Comfort, Sport, etc) while driving westbound on [XXX] in the left lane.  The roadway condition was wet due to heavy rain that just subsided to a light drizzle.
While approaching a Lincoln vehicle with the Highway Drive Assist ("HDA") engaged:
1) The operator decided to actively brake to disengage the HDA mode.  
2) The operator then switched to the right lane successfully.
3) The vehicle's Lane Keep Assist ("LKA") applied steering input during the lane change while the operator manually managed the steering completing the lane change.
4) Within a few seconds of the lane change, the vehicle began to rotate counter-clockwise and the front of the vehicle made contact with the rear passenger side of the Lincoln vehicle in the left lane.
5) After making contact, the GV70 rotated clockwise and travelled off the roadway eventually coming to a stop in a wooded area.  The Lincoln vehicle also left the roadway and came to a stop near the GV70 vehicle in the same wooded area.
6) The GV70 vehicle airbags did not deploy during the incident.
7) Police and first responder medical teams arrived at the incident and the GV70 car was towed away.
HMA and HATCI are actively investigating this incident and are planning to inspect the GV70 vehicle.  An EDR download will be attempted.

10-Day Update
Narrative:
Customer contacted Kia's Consumer Affairs (CA) Department on June [XXX], 2022 indicating that her husband was involved in an accident and the airbags in their 2022 Kia Telluride did not deploy.  Customer reported her husband was driving the subject Telluride at 65mph through a toll southbound on [XXX] when a second vehicle behind the Telluride went through the toll and attempted to squeeze in between the Telluride and a third vehicle on the highway. Customer's husband moved the Telluride to the right to evade the second vehicle and made contact with the right shoulder guardrail.  No other vehicles were involved in the incident.  The vehicle was towed.  When asked by CA, the customer reported that HDA and cruise control were engaged at the time of the incident but customer did not allege that either of those systems caused the accident.
The subject Kia Telluride is equipped with the ADAS Level 2 feature Highway Driving Assist (HDA).  HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance and speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway and helps keep the vehicle between lanes while driving.  HDA may not be able to recognize all traffic situations and may not detect possible collisions due to limitations of the system.  Obstacles such as vehicles, motorcycles, bicycles, pedestrians, unspecified objects and structures that may collide with the vehicle may not be detected.
Based on the description of provided by the customer, the accident was not caused by a failure and/or disengagement of HDA.  Kia has no further information at this time.
***6/[xxx]/15 10-Day Update Incident Report***
On 6/[XXX]/22, Kia spoke with customer's husband regarding the incident. Customer's husband reiterated that his concern was that he believed the airbags should have deployed when he side-swiped the guardrails after he was "cut-off" by another vehicle.

The Waymo AV was traveling in autonomous mode in the rightmost lane on Interstate [XXX] when a Class 8 semi-truck and trailer began to pass it in the adjacent left lane. Before the adjacent Class 8 semi-truck and trailer had fully passed the Waymo AV, it executed a right lane change and its trailer (the right side, rear section) entered the lane in which the Waymo AV was traveling and made contact with the driver side of the Waymo AV cab. The Waymo AV test driver was transported for medical care and the Waymo AV software operator, seated in the passenger seat, later sought medical attention. 
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved in the crash was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment and a vehicle involved was towed away. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative: This single-vehicle crash involved a 2019 Cadillac CT6 that hit a highway median. GM's current understanding of the crash is based on OnStar telematics data and the driver's statements after the crash to an OnStar representative.  Before the crash, the vehicle was proceeding on a highway road with Super Cruise engaged at 70 mph at 09:41:21.  According to the OnStar audio recordings, the driver stated that his knee contacted the steering wheel causing the vehicle to veer left and crash into the highway median.  Telematics data indicates that the vehicle was in Super Cruise "active" mode when the steering wheel was manually moved and the vehicle entered a manual override mode 7 seconds prior to the crash.  According to the AACN report, airbags were not deployed and the driver was not buckled.  According to the OnStar Audio recording the driver hit his head on the roof rail and commented that his back hurt and may need an x-ray, however, it is unknown if the driver sought medical attention at a hospital. Contact to the local police station confirmed the vehicle was towed.

Narrative: This single-vehicle crash involved a 2021 model year Cadillac CT5 V vehicle hitting a deer. GM's current understanding of the crash is based on OnStar telematics data and the driver's statements after the crash to an OnStar representative. Narrative:
The customer was driving in the far left (inside) lane on [XXX] with the pilot assist and the adaptive cruise control activated. The vehicle made an abrupt shift to the left causing the vehicle to hit several orange construction barrels in the area impacting the left side of the vehicle.

Report Type: 1-Day
Narrative:
In this report, the entries above are based on unconfirmed allegations received from the customer through Toyota consumer relations. 
The customer alleged being in an accident, said thanks for saving his life, but also alleged that the lane trace assist failed. Customer stated that he was using cruise control at the time of the accident and does not remember the cruise control speed (but mentioned driving at the speed limit or 10% over the speed limit during the call). The customer alleged that there was sudden down pour of rain and should not have had the cruise control on, and could have been driving safer, but expected the lane trace to have performed better. The customer stated he was using his thumb to decrease the cruise control speed and believes he drove over a large puddle of water and possibly a pothole. The customer also stated that lanes were not detected and the lane tracing assist malfunctioned, causing the vehicle to hydroplane and drift. He reported that the vehicle hit 2-7 trees before coming to a stop. He stated the driver airbag deployed, saving his life, and the driver side seat airbag and driver curtain shield airbags also deployed. He alleges sustaining whiplash, bruising lower abdomen, left knee contusion, cut on left forearm and psychologic stress from the incident. He declined to go to the hospital at the time of the crash but did get a CT scan two days after the crash, which he stated revealed no brain injuries.

Narrative:
On September [XXX], 2021 at 1:54 PM PDT, a Wyamo autonomous vehicles ("Waymo AV") operating in Tempe, AZ was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] Dr. at [XXX]. While in autonomous mode, the Waymo AV began to enter the right lane of a protected double left turn (lane 2) from northbound S. [XXX] to westbound [XXX]. A pickup truck heading southbound on [XXX] had completely crossed the solid double yellow lines of the northbound double left turn lanes and positioned itself in the left lane of the double turn lane (lane 1) facing the wrong direction against traffic and was preparing to make a left turn across lane 2 and the other northbound lanes into the a shopping center parking lot on the east side of [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling in the left lane when the pickup truck began to initiate its left turn from lane 1. The Waymo AV braked and the trained human driver in the Waymo AV (in the drivers seating position) transitioned the vehicle from autonomous mode to manual mode. As the pickup truck made the left turn, the drivers side panels of the pickup truck made contact with the drivers side corner of the Waymo AV, causing moderate damage to the Waymo AV. Damage to the pickup truck is currently unknown. At the time of contact the Waymo AV was in manual mode. 
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Waymo AV was towed away from the scene. Transdev may supplement or update it's reporting with additional information as it may become available. Note: This report is a duplicate to Waymo LLC report (WaymoLLC-202109[XXX]-0 (rev.202109[XXX]174039).

Narrative:
On September [XXX], 2021 at 1:54 PM PDT, a Wyamo autonomous vehicles ("Waymo AV") operating in Tempe, AZ was in a collision involving a pickup truck on [XXX] Dr. at [XXX]. While in autonomous mode, the Waymo AV began to enter the right lane of a protected double left turn (lane 2) from northbound S. [XXX] to westbound [XXX]. A pickup truck heading southbound on [XXX] had completely crossed the solid double yellow lines of the northbound double left turn lanes and positioned itself in the left lane of the double turn lane ("lane 1") facing the wrong direction against traffic and was preparing to make a left turn across lane 2 and the other northbound lanes into the a shopping center parking lot on the east side of [XXX]ive. 
The Waymo AV was traveling in the left lane when the pickup truck began to initiate its left turn from lane 1. The Waymo AV braked and the trained human driver in the Waymo AV (in the drivers seating position) transitioned the vehicle from autonomous mode to manual mode. As the pickup truck made the left turn, the drivers side panels of the pickup truck made contact with the drivers side corner of the Waymo AV, causing moderate damage to the Waymo AV. Damage to the pickup truck is currently unknown. At the time of contact the Waymo AV was in manual mode. 
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because the Waymo AV was towed away from the scene. Transdev may supplement or update it's reporting with additional information as it may become available. Note: This report is a duplicate to Waymo LLC report (WaymoLLC-202109[XXX]-0 (rev.202109[XXX]4039).

Narrative: According to the police report, at the time of the incident a 2016MY Chevrolet Impala was stationary northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane facing northwest.  The 2021MY Kia K5 was traveling northbound on [XXX], in the inside lane approaching the Chevrolet Impala. A 2008MY Honda Civic was traveling northbound on [XXX] in the inside lane behind the Kia K5.  Subsequently, the Kia K5's front struck the Chevrolet Impala's drivers side rear door and rear quarter panel.  After impact, the Impala traveled in a northwesterly, counterclockwise direction into a concrete barrier wall and bounced off the barrier wall and redirected to a northeasterly counterclockwise direction across the northbound lanes when the Honda Civic's front collided into the Chevrolet Impala's and left rear door.  The Chevrolet Impala came to rest facing north, blocking the inside lane. After impact, the Kia K5 traveled in a northeasterly direction across the northbound lanes and came to a final rest on the outside grass shoulder facing west.  The Honda Civic came to final rest blocking the outside lane adjacent to the Chevrolet Impala.  The subject Kia K5 is equipped with Highway Driving Assist (HDA).  HDA is a supplemental system that helps maintain a set distance and speed from the vehicle ahead when driving on a highway and helps keep the vehicle between lanes while driving.  HDA may not be able to recognize all traffic situations and may not detect possible collisions due to limitations of the system.  Obstacles such as vehicles, motorcycles, bicycles, pedestrians, unspecified objects and structures that may collide with the vehicle may not be detected. The owner (father of the driver) of the Kia K5 contacted Kia's Consumer Affairs Department on August [XXX], 2021 indicating that his son was involved in an accident.  The father was not a passenger or witness to the accident.  The father reported that HDA was engaged at the time of the incident and stated that his son "had the autopilot on and there was a vehicle in the middle of the road and it [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] did not notify his son."  According to the father, the police removed the "black box" from the vehicle.  The claims made by the driver's father have not yet been confirmed, and we note that the subject vehicle has no "autopilot" nor does Kia America advertise any ADAS feature as "autopilot."  Kia has no further information at this time.**9/[XXX]/2021 - No incremental information available as of 9/[XXX]/2021 2:26PM (PDT)

10-Day Update
Narrative:
This single-vehicle crash involved a 2018 model year Cadillac CT6 vehicle.  GM's current understanding of the crash is based on OnStar telematics data and the driver's statements after the crash to an OnStar representative.   Before the crash, the vehicle was proceeding straight on a freeway road with Super Cruise engaged.  The driver reported to OnStar that the cause of the crash was his inadvertent contact with the steering wheel that occurred when he bent down to pick something up off the floor of the vehicle.  This is consistent with telematics data, which indicates that the driver provided a manual override input into the steering wheel approximately four seconds before the crash.  This steering wheel input simultaneously disengaged Super Cruise and caused the sequence of events that led to the vehicle crashing into a fixed on-road barrier.  Super Cruise was not active at the time of the crash.  After the Crash, OnStar Emergency contacted the driver and found out the driver was alert and responsive, and requested emergency assistance.  GM believes, but has not confirmed, that the vehicle was towed from the scene.  Telematics data indicates that the driver was not belted at the time of the crash.   GM does not know whether the driver or any vehicle passengers were injured during the crash.
Since the time of submission, there is no new information at this time to update.
